ions about embodied differences as they relate to pedagogy, history, and public participation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aIntellectual disability facilities patientszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aIntellectual disability facilitieszNew York (State)xHistory. 0aIntellectual disability facilitieszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aIntellectual disabilityzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMental retardation -- United States -- History. 0aMental retardation facilities -- New York (State) -- History. 0aMental retardation facilities -- United States -- History. 0aMental retardation facilities patients -- United States -- History. 0aMental retardation facilities patientszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMental retardation facilitieszNew York (State)xHistory. 0aMental retardation facilitieszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMental retardationzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPeople with mental disabilities -- Education -- United States -- History. 0aPeople with mental disabilitiesxEducationzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSociology of disability -- United States. 0aSociology of disabilityzUnited States. 4aCommunication : Communication. 4aCultural Studies : Disabilities. 4aEducation : History of Education. 4aHealth and Medicine : Health and Society. 4aNew York/Regional : New York/Regional. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2014z978311149015140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143845303340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438453033423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438453033/original  a978-3-11-149015-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles